  "text": "One of the simplest approaches to reduce feedback overhead involves each user quantizing his instantaneous vector channel according to a finite collection of vectors (beamformer codebook) that is maintained at both extremes of the link [CITATION_1] . After selecting the optimal quantization vector, receiver feeds back the corresponding codeword index through a B-bit (per user) reverse channel at the beginning of each transmission block. This feedback is used to capture the channel direction information (CDI), and was first considered for point-to-point MIMO channels in [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . System sumrate capacity with only CDI is bounded as the number of users increases because channel quality information (CQI) is not available in transmission to exploit multiuser diversity and obtain the double-logarithmic growth in system throughput with the number of users [CITATION_4] . Based on this, both CDI and CQI feedbacks are necessary if we want to achieve both multiplexing and multiuser diversity gains at the same time. As expected, we later show that CQI should be the channel magnitude in low Tx power regime, while it should be proportional to the signal-to-interference power ratio (SIR) when Tx power is high.",
